00:37:01.281 --> 00:37:07.700
some agency handed out blankets during the
cold part of the year and she made hers into

00:37:07.700 --> 00:37:08.700
a coat, jacket.

00:37:08.700 --> 00:37:13.490
[pause]

00:37:13.490 --> 00:37:21.720
The next photo is a poor woman sitting at
Inspiration Point, bent down looking like

00:37:21.720 --> 00:37:28.579
she's experiencing some sort of despair, if
her posture is any indication.

00:37:28.579 --> 00:37:36.890
And the last one is on Second Street at the
Knoll Chair Store and once again it takes

00:37:36.890 --> 00:37:45.690
a few seconds to look to see the person sleeping
just outside the light.

00:37:45.690 --> 00:37:52.000
People say, "Well, if there are shelters,
why do some of these women stay outside and

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.940
not go to the shelters?" And let's assume
for purposes of the discussion that there

00:37:55.940 --> 00:37:58.470
are shelter beds.

00:37:58.470 --> 00:38:03.589
Well, we were told many, many times, as a
matter of fact it was a constant theme from

00:38:03.589 --> 00:38:10.529
the women we spoke to, almost regardless of
their mental condition that they didn't like

00:38:10.529 --> 00:38:17.000
the shelters because they're very noisy which
was frightening; some of the men there they

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:21.059
felt were dangerous, they didn't want to be
around them; and who wants to sleep a few

00:38:21.059 --> 00:38:25.410
feet away from somebody that you don't know
if they're crazy or violent or whatever. And

00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:30.770
so some of the women stayed away from the
shelters. It's not that they were ungrateful;

00:38:30.770 --> 00:38:36.930
it's that they wanted to take care of themselves,
they can be frightening places.

00:38:36.930 --> 00:38:41.861
And I was talking to a retired city attorney
from Santa Monica and saying, "Well would

00:38:41.861 --> 00:38:46.150
you want to sleep in a shelter?" "Actually
no." He said, "All they would like is a small

00:38:46.150 --> 00:38:51.920
room of their own," assuming that they're
well enough to take care of it.

00:38:51.920 --> 00:38:54.339
[pause]

00:38:54.339 --> 00:39:04.039
[sound of papers shuffling]

00:39:04.039 --> 00:39:11.230
So people say, "How did it happen? How did
this happen?" Well you can see some of the

00:39:11.230 --> 00:39:17.630
reasons just from the stories of some of the
women that I've told you about today. The

00:39:17.630 --> 00:39:23.520
mental illness, and there's a period in this
country when there was a deinstitutionalization

00:39:23.520 --> 00:39:27.750
of the mentally ill; they were moved out of
mental hospitals supposedly into community

00:39:27.750 --> 00:39:32.950
care centers which, of course, were never
funded. As Daniel Patrick Moynihan said at

00:39:32.950 --> 00:39:37.520
the time, "We're capable of doing this and
we do it with regularity." Congress failed

00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:41.549
to take care of the problem that it said it
would take care of.

00:39:41.549 --> 00:39:46.010
People were first moved away from the mental
hospitals in the 60s and the 70s. They were

00:39:46.010 --> 00:39:53.210
terrible places. People were not treated,
often they were just drugged to control really

00:39:53.210 --> 00:39:59.490
aberrant or violent behavior. And the kinds
of fancy psychotropic drugs that we have today

00:39:59.490 --> 00:40:02.940
did not exist. I mean one can appreciate the
quandary of people who are trying to take

00:40:02.940 --> 00:40:08.710
care of severely, severely mentally ill people,
nevertheless, a bad situation all around.

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:16.960
And so there was the deinstitutionalization
that was pushed by many people in the 60s

00:40:16.960 --> 00:40:21.829
and the 70s who were trying to break away
from other perceived authoritarian structures.

00:40:21.829 --> 00:40:28.760
The problem was there wasn't much to replace
it with. We didn't, the society didn't fund

00:40:28.760 --> 00:40:35.200
better care and so what you had is what we
see on the streets today.

00:40:35.200 --> 00:40:41.790
We see people who are out of the mental, are
out of a mental care system and free, but

00:40:41.790 --> 00:40:46.000
what are they free to do? They're free to
go to roam through a garbage can, they're

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.279
free to sleep in any doorway that they want.

00:40:48.279 --> 00:40:53.271
There's a lot of discussion legally as well
about what kinds of restrictions should be

00:40:53.271 --> 00:40:59.670
put on a mentally ill person. California law
for many years only allowed involuntary commitment

00:40:59.670 --> 00:41:07.849
if the person was an immediate danger to him
or herself or to another, which didn't really

00:41:07.849 --> 00:41:15.250
allow for evidence from those people who knew
the mentally ill person best about whole series

00:41:15.250 --> 00:41:22.019
of events perhaps culminating in something
or culminating, or other kinds of behavior

00:41:22.019 --> 00:41:26.730
being told to the court which would clearly
indicate a severe mental illness. That has

00:41:26.730 --> 00:41:30.410
been changed. There is a better evidentiary
requirement now; more evidence can get in;

00:41:30.410 --> 00:41:37.619
families can get more involuntary commitment
if that's what they seek. But that's still

00:41:37.619 --> 00:41:40.789
a very, very controversial topic.

00:41:40.789 --> 00:41:46.010
If I had asked, we did ask some of the women
that we spoke to what would they like, where

00:41:46.010 --> 00:41:52.289
would they like to be? And I don't think either
of us had the courage to ask any of them,

00:41:52.289 --> 00:41:55.990
"Would you prefer involuntary commitment?"
We know the answer. It would have been no.

00:41:55.990 --> 00:41:58.010
So I mean it's a very difficult subject.

00:41:58.010 --> 00:41:59.660
[pause]

00:41:59.660 --> 00:42:09.589
So people ask me, "So what are they like?"
And "What are homeless people like? What are

00:42:09.589 --> 00:42:19.569
homeless women like?" Well, it's very difficult,
it's very difficult for me to give a short

00:42:19.569 --> 00:42:24.481
answer in a sentence or two. But let me just
read you a couple of, a few paragraphs from

00:42:24.481 --> 00:42:29.579
the beginning of the book which I think sums
it up, at least from our point of view.

00:42:29.579 --> 00:42:34.099
"They sit on the grass under trees in the
parks. They sit in filthy cars in front of

00:42:34.099 --> 00:42:41.420
City Hall. They sit on benches, park benches,
bus benches, benches on Third Street Promenade,

00:42:41.420 --> 00:42:46.049
benches on the pier. They stand in doorways.
They sleep in doorways. They rummage through

00:42:46.049 --> 00:42:49.900
trash cans. They panhandle. They visit with
friends.

00:42:49.900 --> 00:42:56.980
They move around -- walking, shuffling, staggering,
often looking down, usually alone, burdened

00:42:56.980 --> 00:43:02.250
by bags and backpacks, pushing shopping carts
spilling over with their possessions.

00:43:02.250 --> 00:43:10.140
They are distressed, calm, disoriented, rational,
incoherent, articulate, filthy, clean, angry,

00:43:10.140 --> 00:43:17.220
forgiving, pretty, plain, resigned, hopeful,
brave, afraid, unspoken to.

00:43:17.220 --> 00:43:23.799
They write poetry. They paint. They drink
too much. They use drugs. They're sober. Their

00:43:23.799 --> 00:43:28.200
families don't know where they are. Their
families kicked them out. Their families want

00:43:28.200 --> 00:43:29.200
them to come home.

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:35.490
They come from far away. They are home grown.
They appreciate the kindness of strangers.

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:37.400
They want to be left alone.

00:43:37.400 --> 00:43:43.119
They're ex-cons. They're church goers. They're
old and they're young. They hate the cold,

00:43:43.119 --> 00:43:49.099
the rain, the wind. They stay out of the heat
of the sun. They don't trust the police. They

00:43:49.099 --> 00:43:51.880
had a job once. They never worked.

00:43:51.880 --> 00:43:57.579
One grabs at people as she walks by. Another
howls silently. Many talk to themselves when

00:43:57.579 --> 00:44:01.930
they think nobody's listening. They're always
poor.

00:44:01.930 --> 00:44:05.799
They say they live outside because they don't
qualify for assistance. They say they don't

00:44:05.799 --> 00:44:10.210
qualify for assistance because they aren't
insane or a drunk or an addict or they'll

00:44:10.210 --> 00:44:14.660
lose their freedom if they go inside, or they're
afraid of the men at the shelters, or the

00:44:14.660 --> 00:44:18.970
bank stole all their money, or they're being
followed by a man who assumes many shapes

00:44:18.970 --> 00:44:23.510
and identities, or the FBI and the CIA are
after them, or they're helping the police

00:44:23.510 --> 00:44:27.360
find a serial killer, or nobody asked them
if they wanted an apartment and there are

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:30.010
no apartments available to them anyway.

00:44:30.010 --> 00:44:35.599
Many have a hard time knowing what they think
much less saying it because their thoughts

00:44:35.599 --> 00:44:40.400
are muddled and their words don't come out
right. They hear extra voices in their heads,

00:44:40.400 --> 00:44:44.640
they see things the rest of us don't see,
and they believe things the rest of us don't

00:44:44.640 --> 00:44:45.640
believe.

00:44:45.640 --> 00:44:50.829
Who are they? They're the homeless women of
Santa Monica. They are the homeless women

00:44:50.829 --> 00:44:52.230
everywhere."

00:44:52.230 --> 00:44:54.460
Thank you.

00:44:54.460 --> 00:44:56.540
[applause]

00:44:56.540 --> 00:44:59.400
[sound of dog barking]

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:00.400
Thank you.

00:45:00.400 --> 00:45:02.480
I take that as applause. [laughs]

00:45:02.480 --> 00:45:03.480
[laughter]

00:45:03.480 --> 00:45:07.690
&gt;&gt;Julie Wiskirchen: Does anybody have any
questions for Frances or her son, Ian, the

00:45:07.690 --> 00:45:08.690
photographer is here as well?

00:45:08.690 --> 00:45:09.690
[pause]

00:45:09.690 --> 00:45:10.690
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: Anyone?

00:45:10.690 --> 00:45:11.690
[pause]

00:45:11.690 --> 00:45:12.690
&gt;&gt;male #1: I actually have a question because
I've spoken to a bunch of homeless people

00:45:12.690 --> 00:45:56.880
in Santa Monica and I find them really interesting
and I wanted to just see if your take though

00:45:56.880 --> 00:45:57.880
was that if you found this to be correct that
everybody is fearful about talking to people.

00:45:57.880 --> 00:45:58.880
They might look fascinating and you see that
some of these people are highly intelligent

00:45:58.880 --> 00:45:59.880
and creative but there's always the fear that
they are gonna be nuts and they're gonna go

00:45:59.880 --> 00:46:00.880
off on you, go crazy. I mean is that often
the case or do you think it's not so much

00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:01.880
the case when you talk to them?

00:46:01.880 --> 00:46:02.880
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: Well as I said no we, we
antici--, we weren't sure about initial reactions

00:46:02.880 --> 00:46:06.770
either when we began. And what we found among
the women was that there was really no need

00:46:06.770 --> 00:46:12.510
to be anxious or afraid. And there was only
one woman I spoke to who, whose face completely

00:46:12.510 --> 00:46:18.730
changed expression and she was going into
a psychotic episode and I stepped back and

00:46:18.730 --> 00:46:22.120
gave her space, but it didn't accelerate into
anything. And I said, "Thank you and good

00:46:22.120 --> 00:46:23.120
bye."

00:46:23.120 --> 00:46:28.609
But by that time we'd had a lot of experience.
We spoke to hundreds of people, not all of

00:46:28.609 --> 00:46:34.349
them of course got in the book. But as I mentioned
an untreated, seriously, mentally ill male

00:46:34.349 --> 00:46:45.650
is a different person from the counterpart
who is a female. And so we were wary, that's

00:46:45.650 --> 00:46:48.410
why we stopped interviewing men.

00:46:48.410 --> 00:46:56.369
We were out so long too that we got to the
point where we could pick out the most subtle

00:46:56.369 --> 00:47:02.670
body language and see that somebody was homeless
and they were trying to hide it. And in those

00:47:02.670 --> 00:47:06.180
cases we were hesitant to go up sometimes
'cause you didn't want to embarrass them and

00:47:06.180 --> 00:47:10.339
make them feel -- but you could tell certain
things. The way a person walked, all sorts

00:47:10.339 --> 00:47:14.590
of things. What their feet looked like. And
we got, it got to the point where we had a

00:47:14.590 --> 00:47:17.630
pretty good read on the person's personality.

00:47:17.630 --> 00:47:18.630
[pause]

00:47:18.630 --> 00:47:27.130
&gt;&gt;male #2: What's the police, like the police
do they, what are their sort of instructions

00:47:27.130 --> 00:47:28.839
on how to deal with the homeless?

00:47:28.839 --> 00:47:33.369
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: Well there is a liaison,
a homeless liaison in the Santa Monica Police

00:47:33.369 --> 00:47:34.369
Department.

00:47:34.369 --> 00:47:38.030
[pause]

00:47:38.030 --> 00:47:44.650
What we heard from a lot of the women was
that they felt uncared for by the police or

00:47:44.650 --> 00:47:54.981
hassled. And the City's a little bit schizophrenic
in its approach sometimes. There are these

00:47:54.981 --> 00:48:01.430
extraordinary programs which are online, so
anyone can read what kind of care or services

00:48:01.430 --> 00:48:02.950
are available for homeless people.

00:48:02.950 --> 00:48:09.860
At the same time there are signs in various
businesses doorways, "Don't sleep here." And

00:48:09.860 --> 00:48:13.910
if somebody sleeps there in violation of the
warning on the sign, the police can pick them

00:48:13.910 --> 00:48:18.810
up. There are other places where sometimes
people are sleeping [clears throat] excuse

00:48:18.810 --> 00:48:24.380
me, which I'll show my bias like in the industrial
section there's nobody there. There doesn't

00:48:24.380 --> 00:48:26.799
really seem to be a problem where the person
will be told in the middle of the night, "Get

00:48:26.799 --> 00:48:27.799
up and move on."

00:48:27.799 --> 00:48:34.779
So I think it's not the easiest relationship.
I also understand that the police probably

00:48:34.779 --> 00:48:41.030
spend a huge percentage of their time on problems
"created by homeless people." So that's an

00:48:41.030 --> 00:48:44.250
issue for them I'm sure. It's a complicated
matter.

00:48:44.250 --> 00:48:47.950
[pause]

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:53.849
My sense is that probably more, my sense is
that most of the women don't feel that the

00:48:53.849 --> 00:48:55.240
police are their ally. That's my sense.

00:48:55.240 --> 00:49:02.319
&gt;&gt;male #3: So I've got a question for you.
Well first, thanks so much for making visible

00:49:02.319 --> 00:49:05.230
and pursuing this project. We really appreciate
it.

00:49:05.230 --> 00:49:06.230
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: You're welcome.

00:49:06.230 --> 00:49:13.700
&gt;&gt;male #3: And a question for I think Ian
and for you both is what do the subjects of

00:49:13.700 --> 00:49:19.359
your photos think and have you had a chance
to share with them? I know you talked a little

00:49:19.359 --> 00:49:20.359
bit about it but --

00:49:20.359 --> 00:49:25.210
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: They all really love it.
It's very touching. You don't always know

00:49:25.210 --> 00:49:29.200
if that will be the case even if you went
forth with permissions and signed releases

00:49:29.200 --> 00:49:34.559
and all that. There are times when people
say things and then when they look back they

00:49:34.559 --> 00:49:39.359
didn't quite fully understand that it would
be made public. And yet we have a very, very

00:49:39.359 --> 00:49:44.250
positive response. We spent more days at Daybreak
again, for example, giving books to the women

00:49:44.250 --> 00:49:49.130
there. They're so pleased. One woman said,
"Look at this picture. It made me remember

00:49:49.130 --> 00:49:51.760
that I used to smile." It was touching.

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:59.869
And we feel that we have a very good relationship
with the homeless community.

00:49:59.869 --> 00:50:02.599
&gt;&gt;male #3: Thanks.

00:50:02.599 --> 00:50:03.599
[pause]

00:50:03.599 --> 00:50:11.420
&gt;&gt;female #1: Thank you for coming. When you
started this project, you probably had some

00:50:11.420 --> 00:50:15.819
preconceived notions about homeless and what
for you is the one thing that changed the

00:50:15.819 --> 00:50:17.450
most when you finished this project?

00:50:17.450 --> 00:50:19.089
[pause]

00:50:19.089 --> 00:50:30.670
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: I feel, well I didn't know
what to expect. I don't think Ian did either.

00:50:30.670 --> 00:50:40.750
But I feel that I understand the population
better and it was a huge educational experience.

00:50:40.750 --> 00:50:44.970
And we spoke to not only homeless people,
we spoke to people in the city, we spoke to

00:50:44.970 --> 00:50:51.250
citizens, we spoke to social service providers,
psychiatrists, everybody you can think about

00:50:51.250 --> 00:50:55.339
to try and get a complete picture. The main
source of information frankly though was the

00:50:55.339 --> 00:50:58.369
women. I mean really there's no question about
that.

00:50:58.369 --> 00:51:11.319
I just feel comfortable with the idea of them.
I don't, and I see them very, very much. So

00:51:11.319 --> 00:51:15.380
in the old days, it's easier to look away
sometimes. Once we started working on this

00:51:15.380 --> 00:51:20.930
book, it got to the point that all I could
see on the street were homeless women. And

00:51:20.930 --> 00:51:26.360
sometimes I would not go out. I would not
take my usual walk. I needed a break. It would

00:51:26.360 --> 00:51:28.150
be all I could see.

00:51:28.150 --> 00:51:35.220
And so it certainly increased my information
and my knowledge about a part of humanity

00:51:35.220 --> 00:51:36.550
I didn't know too much about.

00:51:36.550 --> 00:51:38.759
Um-hum.

00:51:38.759 --> 00:51:40.970
[pause]

00:51:40.970 --> 00:51:48.119
&gt;&gt;Ian Noble: I think for me -- is this working?
Cool. I think for me it was just the level

00:51:48.119 --> 00:51:53.000
of mental illness, how many really were suffering
from something serious. I'd always heard the

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:56.260
a third, and a third, and a third argument.
Some people are down on their luck, they'll

00:51:56.260 --> 00:52:00.430
be back on their feet soon. Some are addicts
or alcoholics and the other third is mentally

00:52:00.430 --> 00:52:06.069
ill. But just the percentage of people who
seem to be suffering from something very serious

00:52:06.069 --> 00:52:11.270
was far beyond that and that's really what
struck me above anything else, I think.

00:52:11.270 --> 00:52:17.569
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: If I could just add one thought
to that. We wondered why that was. And we

00:52:17.569 --> 00:52:23.880
came to the conclusion that in the sense we
had a self-selected group. People who were

00:52:23.880 --> 00:52:28.750
able to take care of themselves better, get
back into the employment world, or get themselves

00:52:28.750 --> 00:52:35.019
back to a family member who could assist,
were doing that.

00:52:35.019 --> 00:52:40.779
The people that we saw were the ones who were
sitting and kind of hiding in the parks or

00:52:40.779 --> 00:52:47.160
cocooning in the parks, or hoping that they
would be alright. Not that some are not social

00:52:47.160 --> 00:52:51.779
and visiting with each other, but in general
we felt that we were exposed to the most vulnerable

00:52:51.779 --> 00:52:55.369
for the most part of the group. And that's
why they were self-selected. They couldn't

00:52:55.369 --> 00:52:57.381
do anything else but what they were doing.

00:52:57.381 --> 00:52:58.539
[pause]

00:52:58.539 --> 00:53:04.390
&gt;&gt;Julie Wiskirchen: Any other questions?

00:53:04.390 --> 00:53:05.559
[pause]

00:53:05.559 --> 00:53:11.859
&gt;&gt;male #4: You talked about some of the issues
that were keeping them away from shelters.

00:53:11.859 --> 00:53:16.990
When you were speaking to people who were
involved in shelters, did you get the sense

00:53:16.990 --> 00:53:22.240
that they all understood that and it was simply
an issue of funding of administrating or that

00:53:22.240 --> 00:53:30.030
that was, that they didn't fully understand
the sort of issues that were, what they were

00:53:30.030 --> 00:53:34.690
doing maybe that was driving people away or
what they would need to do to be, bring more

00:53:34.690 --> 00:53:35.690
people in?

00:53:35.690 --> 00:53:41.960
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: I think that most people
that were involved in administering the shelters

00:53:41.960 --> 00:53:46.720
or the programs understood. I also think at
this particular time when we were doing the

00:53:46.720 --> 00:53:54.160
book they were inundated and you can't, and
so it was a scramble, "Can we get this bed

00:53:54.160 --> 00:53:56.809
for so and so. Somebody is calling and saying
they have two people."

00:53:56.809 --> 00:54:04.349
I think that it's probably quieter now. I
know that there's been relocation of some

00:54:04.349 --> 00:54:11.059
of the programs and they seem to be much more
orderly on the outside which I'm going to

00:54:11.059 --> 00:54:16.089
suggest or hope to suggest that it's more
orderly on the inside. The people at Daybreak

00:54:16.089 --> 00:54:21.640
of course always understood what was going
on and how to provide a safe environment for

00:54:21.640 --> 00:54:22.640
the women.

00:54:22.640 --> 00:54:28.490
And I really believe in equality of the sexes
and I can also say I think that women do need

00:54:28.490 --> 00:54:33.950
more protection. On the streets they're subject
to -- I mean the statistics are horrifying

00:54:33.950 --> 00:54:40.839
 -- to far greater numbers of assaults and
rapes and robberies. And many women told us

00:54:40.839 --> 00:54:44.839
about their terrible experiences being on
the street.

00:54:44.839 --> 00:54:48.119
So I do think that most people are aware.

00:54:48.119 --> 00:55:03.980
&gt;&gt;male #5: Is there something particular about
Santa Monica that there's been such a concentration

00:55:03.980 --> 00:55:04.980
of homeless people versus like Pasadena or
Beverly Hills or other affluent communities?

00:55:04.980 --> 00:55:07.380
&gt;&gt;Frances Noble: Oh sure. Santa Monica what
